# to get the detailed info about a pod 
  kubectl describe pod <podname>

kubectl edit pod <pod_name>
Purpose:
It opens the YAML definition of the specified Kubernetes pod in your default text editor, allowing you to edit the pod's configuration live.

How it works:
Retrieves the resource
kubectl fetches the current configuration of the pod named <pod_name> from the Kubernetes API server.

Opens in an editor

Uses the editor defined in the environment variables:
$KUBE_EDITOR (highest priority)
$EDITOR
Defaults to vi (Linux/macOS) or notepad (Windows) if none are set.
Applies changes
When you save and close the editor:

kubectl sends the updated YAML back to the API server.
Kubernetes attempts to apply the changes immediately.
Important Notes:
Pods are immutable for most fields — you cannot change certain properties (like container images, ports, or volumes) directly.
If you try, Kubernetes will reject the update.
For changes to container specs, you usually need to update the Deployment (or other controller) that manages the pod, not the pod itself.
Editing a pod directly is mostly used for debugging or quick fixes (e.g., changing labels, annotations, or environment variables in some cases).
✅ Example:

Bash

Copy code
kubectl edit pod my-app-pod
This will open the YAML for my-app-pod in your editor. After saving, Kubernetes will apply the allowed changes
